	<p  line-height:150% style="font-size: 26px; font-family:calibri;margin-left:100px;" align="justify"><font color="#202020"><strong>Effects on Vineyards</p></font></strong>
	
	
  <p line-height:150% style="font-size: 24px; font-family:calibri;margin-left:100px;" align="justify"><font color="#202020">
California is the largest producer of wine in USA. If California would itself a country it would be 4th largest wine producing country.The state of California has issued drought state emergency in the month of December,worries continue to mount over the economic implications of the region's long-lasting dry weather, especially for the wine industry. While grape vines are currently in their dormant stage and do not have any specific water needs, a drought in combination with warmer-than-normal temperatures can tease them into waking up earlier. After waking up, the vines will bud, creating an even bigger challenge for growers as the potential for frost still looms. In addition, the lack of rain will increase the salt content in the soil, as fall rains usually wash away some salt concentration. A high salt concentration creates a toxic environment for grape vine roots, making it hard for them to absorb nutrients and thus produce a good crop.2012 and 2013 were productive years for the wine industry so the weather won't affect till 2016 but due severe drought conditions in the later part of 2013 and 2014 as of now, if the vineyards owner have planted new grape vines than the result would be hazardous as predicted by many wine scholars. From 2015-2016 onwards the wine industry will face terrible situation because of the drought. </font></p>
<p  line-height:150% style="font-size: 26px; font-family:calibri;margin-left:100px;" align="justify"><font color="#202020"><strong>Napa Valley</p></font></strong><p  line-height:150% style="font-size: 24px; font-family:calibri;margin-left:100px;" align="justify"><font color="#202020"> Largest producer of American wines in USA is facing severe drought on the vineyards. Wine production would be substantially decreased from year 2014. Many wine crops have dried due to lack of rainfall.</font></p>
<p  line-height:150% style="font-size: 24px; font-family:calibri;margin-left:100px;" align="justify"><font color="#202020">So as to summarize if the situation prevails in the upcoming years the California wine industry will face catastrophic damage to the vineyards and that will impact the GDP of the whole country.</font></p></td>
